idCitation.resTitle: Tanzania 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex: Second-Order Administrative Divisions, 2000-2020

dataIdInfo.idPurp: The U.S. Census Bureau is providing annual subnational five-year age group population estimates by sex for 2000 to 2020 in a geographic information system (GIS), funded by the U.S. President’s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).
dataIdInfo.idAbs: Annual five-year age group population estimates by sex for 2000 to 2020 for the second-order administrative divisions of Tanzania were prepared by the U.S. Census Bureau for joining (linking) to this boundary shapefile as attribute data. The estimates are consistent with the midyear national projections from the U.S. Census Bureau International Data Base (IDB).

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
SUBNATIONAL DIVISIONS
Tanzania's first-order administrative divisions: 30 regions as reported in the 2012 Census.
Tanzania's second-order administrative divisions: 169 districts as reported in the 2012 Census.
SHAPEFILES
The original shapefile contained polygons for the 169 districts (i.e., the second-order administrative divisions). The U.S. Census Bureau created a new shapefile by aligning the boundaries of the original to the “Large Scale International Boundary Line” polygon file (2011) from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues.
The resulting shapefile contains 175 polygons representing Tanzania's 169 districts and 6 inland waterbodies.
The Census Bureau cannot guarantee the precision of the boundary placements.
CENSUS DATA
The POPULATION DISTRIBUTION BY AGE AND SEX [2012 Census] (cited in “Credits”) provided raw 5-year age group counts from the 2012 census for males, females, and both sexes for the 169 districts and 30 regions. The 2002 CENSUS POPULATION DISTRIBUTION AS PER 2012 POPULATION CENSUS ADMINISTRATIVE UNITS (cited in "Credits") provided raw 5-year age group counts from the 2002 census for males, females, and both sexes for the 169 districts and 30 regions distributed to 2012 administrative units.
2000-2020 ESTIMATES
The estimates for the 5-year age groups between ages 0 to 79 and for ages 80-and-over by sex were calculated in two steps: (1) The logistic growth rate method was used with 2002 and 2012 census populations to calculate population controls for the 169 districts and 30 regions for 2000-2020. The controls are consistent with the estimates and projections for Tanzania from the INTERNATIONAL DATA BASE. To ensure consistent population trends during the 2000-2020 time span, 2002 census population numbers adjusted to the 2012 administrative units were utilized (see "Credits"). (2) The 5-year age group estimates for the districts and regions were calculated using the Iterative Proportional Fitting method. The estimates are consistent with both the controls from step 1 and the 5-year age group estimates and projections by sex for Tanzania from the INTERNATIONAL DATA BASE.
The above methods are described in the document “Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas,” and web addresses for accessing it are given at the end of this section.
FEATURES AND ATTRIBUTES DETAILS
The 2000-2020 population estimates for the 169 districts (and for the first-order administrative division, 30 regions) are provided in the following two tables: • The Unicode tab-delimited text file (table) "Tanzania_5yr_age_sex_2000-2020_uscb_aug2016.txt,” which can be joined to the shapefile via the common field “GEO_MATCH." • The Excel table "Tanzania_5yr_age_sex_2000-2020_508_uscb_aug2016.xlsx," formatted for accessibility in compliance with Section 508 of the U.S. Government’s Federal Rehabilitation Act.
For the subnational areas the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN) “approved” names from the NGA GEOnet Names Server (cited in “Credits”) were used. For any area that a BGN name was not available, the name from the national census was used. Official codes for the subnational areas from the country’s national statistical office, when available, are entered in the “NSO_CODE” field in both the text and Excel tables. Information on any alternate area names or recent name or boundary changes is entered in the “COMMENT” field.
A partial listing of the fields in the tables in both the Excel and Unicode text files, including those containing the age group populations for both sexes, males, and females for the year 2000 (whose field headings are denoted “B,” “M,” and “F” respectively), follows:

ADDITIONAL INFORMATION
More detail on the U.S. Census Bureau subnational age and sex group estimates and maps for PEPFAR can be found in the document “Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository,” and it includes a data dictionary identical to that in the Excel table. Web addresses to access the document are given below.
ACCESS
The U.S. Census Bureau’s products for PEPFAR can be accessed from the following websites in the SPATIAL DATA REPOSITORY:
Zipped file containing geographic boundary data, tables with subnational population estimates, and instructions for linking (joining) the text file to the geographic boundary data: http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/home/. This web address also provides access to data and maps from the DHS (Demographic and Health Surveys) Program.
Instructions for linking the text file to the geographic boundary data can also be found at http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/references/ReadMe_PopLinkageToShapefile_Instructions.pdf.
Methods documents:
“Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository”: http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/references/geo_metadata_pgs_uscb_v4_sep16.pdf.
“Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas”: http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/references/subntl_pop_est_methods_pgs_uscb_sep16.pdf.
All of the above documents, tables, and geographic boundary data (zipped) can also be accessed through the U.S. CENSUS BUREAU, INTERNATIONAL PROGRAMS, SUBNATIONAL MAPPING FOR ADMINISTRATIVE AREAS: U.S. PRESIDENT’S EMERGENCY PLAN FOR AIDS RELIEF, available at http://www.census.gov/population/international/data/mapping/spatialdata.html.
